Package ie.gmit.dip

Class IterativeStringSplitter

  • java.lang.Object
    • ie.gmit.dip.IterativeStringSplitter
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    AbstractParser<java.lang.String,​java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.String>>
    public class IterativeStringSplitter
extends java.lang.Object
implements AbstractParser<java.lang.String,​java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.String>>
    The class IterativeStringSplitter is a concrete type that implements the AbstractParser interface. String splitting is a frequent task when parsing files and other streams. Having multiple utility classes which allow for various splitting operations is useful for anyone carrying out a lot of file parsing operations. The IterativeStringSplitter is configured with a set of ordered delimiters (i.e. String types, perhaps in the form of regular expressions) which are used to iteratively split a string into an ordered ArrayList of String types, which preserves the original order of elements in the String type provided as input. Note that an important feature of this parser is that it aims to preserve, as closely as possible, the original String type which is being split. Therefore, the delimiters which are used as the input for the String.split() method, are added to the final ArrayList as elements in the order they appeared/splitting occurred. In order to achieve this, the ArrayList of delimiters is accompanied by a HashMap of delimiters, which is used to map a given regular expression/delimiter to a String which is substituted for that regular expression after splitting occurs i.e. the regular expression used for splitting is mapped to an equivalent String type which is used to reconstruct the original String with its original delimiters preserved.

      • getDefaultDelimiterOrder

        public java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.String> getDefaultDelimiterOrder()
        Getter method which defines a default ArrayList of delimiters use to split the String. These delimiters have a natural order, that is, the string is parsed by new line characters first, then by spaces (words), then by periods (i.e. sentences), commas (,) and semicolons (;). Any order of delimiters can of course be used. Running time is effectively is the sum of the O(c) add operations.
        Returns:
        delimiterOrder an ArrayList of delimiters of String types in the order they are used to split the String.

      • parse

        public java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.String> parse()
                                            throws java.lang.Exception
        The parse() method which is used to iteratively split the string. The order of operations is as follows. Convert the original string to an ArrayList with a single element. For each delimiter in the this.delimiterOrder ArrayList, loop over all of the strings in the input. If the original string contains the mapped delimiter character, then split the String into individual elements based on that delimiter, and add the split elements to a temporary array, along with the correct number of delimiters characters. If the original String does not contain the delimiter character, then no split is necessary, and the original String is simply added to the temporary array. The original ArrayList (of one element) is replaced with the new array of potentially multiple elements, and this list of String types is now iteratively split by the next delimiter. A comment on running time and Big-O notation. The three nested for loops over the delimiters, the ArrayList of strings and finally the split strings imply an O(n*m*l) cubic running time where n is the number of delimiters, m is the number of String types to split, and m is the number of String types returned from splitting the String m. The actual running time will vary depending on the number of delimiters to split on, and the characters in the initial String being split.
        Specified by:
        parse in interface AbstractParser<java.lang.String,​java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.String>>
        Returns:
        ArrayList an ArrayList of split String types.
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - if there is an error during splitting.
